    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is a fundamental concept in the 14th Amendment that ensures the government respects fundamental rights and liberties beyond just procedural requirements. It's been a powerful tool in expanding civil rights, particularly in cases like Plessy v. Ferguson (1896) where it was used to strike down segregation laws, and Roe v. Wade (1973) where it protected a woman's right to choose. The Supreme Court has consistently applied substantive due process to safeguard personal liberties, such as freedom of speech, freedom of association, and reproductive rights, even when the Constitution's text doesn't explicitly mention them.",
      "source": "target",
